===================================================
INGREDIENTS
===================================================

For the stock: 
    1 whole chicken 
    chicken wings, 1 lbs
    ?


For the soup: 
    ~5-7 medium leeks, thinly sliced white & pale green parts, 750g
    shallot, thiny sliced (1/2 cup)
    yellow onion, finely diced (100g) 
    garlic, 3 cloves, minced (~1 tbsp) 

    yukon gold potatoes, peeled and cut into 1/2 inch cubes, ~3.3 lbs (after peeling)
        this will be 10-12 medium potatoes or 6-8 large ones

    5 bacon strips
    unsalted butter, 5 tbsp 
    extra-virgin olive oil, 2 tbsp 

    chicken stock, 2.5 quarts (10 cups)
    heavy cream, 1/2 cup, warmed 
    buttermilk, 1/2 cup 
    white miso, 1.5 tbsp 

    salt, 1.5 tbsp (adjust to taste) 
    white pepper, 1 tsp ground
    nutmeg, 1/4 tsp (freshly grated if possible) 
    lemon juice, 1 tbsp 

    2 bay leaves
    4 sprigs of fresh thyme
    4 sprigs of parsley


===================================================
STOCK PREPARATION 
===================================================

The production of a white chicken stock, or fond blanc, represents one of the most foundational and technically demanding exercises in the classical culinary arts, particularly when the end application is a refined potato-leek soup. Unlike a brown stock, which relies on the Maillard reaction and caramelization achieved through roasting, a white stock focuses on the pure extraction of collagen and aromatic essences without the introduction of dark pigments or roasted flavor compounds.1 In the context of a pressure-cooked environment reaching 12 PSI, the chef must navigate a specific set of thermodynamic and biochemical variables to ensure that the increased temperature does not emulsify lipids or degrade the delicate volatile compounds of the mirepoix blanc.4 This report provides an exhaustive examination of the ingredient selection and procedural algorithms required to produce a master-level stock tailored for the structural and flavor requirements of a starch-heavy, leek-centric soup.
Thermodynamic Dynamics of High-Pressure Extraction at 12 PSI
The use of a pressure vessel fundamentally alters the rate of collagen hydrolysis. At standard atmospheric pressure at sea level, water boils at  (), a temperature that requires six to eight hours of simmering to effectively convert the collagen in chicken bones into gelatin.1 A pressure cooker operating at 12 PSI (approximately 0.8 bar above atmospheric pressure) raises the boiling point of the liquid. The relationship between pressure and boiling point is described by the Clausius-Clapeyron equation, which predicts that at 12 PSI, the internal temperature reaches approximately  ().4
While many modern recipes are calibrated for 15 PSI ( / ), the 12 PSI environment is often preferred by professional sauciers for white stock because it is less aggressive.4 At , there is a heightened risk of "over-extraction," where the bones begin to release calcium and other minerals that can impart a chalky or bitter taste.10 The 12 PSI threshold allows for rapid gelatin extraction while maintaining a more nuanced aromatic profile. However, this lower temperature necessitates a temporal adjustment. Based on the logic of extraction kinetics, a recipe designed for 90 minutes at 15 PSI requires an increase of approximately 20% to 50% in duration to achieve the same molecular breakdown at 12 PSI.12
