The Mechanics of Extraction: A Comprehensive Algorithm
The production of a masterful stock requires a meticulous approach to cleaning and thermal management. The following steps must be followed with precision to ensure clarity and concentration.
a) The Blanch and Refresh Protocol
Clarity in a white stock is achieved by removing the blood and denatured proteins from the poultry before the primary extraction begins.
Place the whole chicken and the pound of wings in a large stockpot and cover with cold tap water.1
Bring the water to a rapid, rolling boil. Maintain the boil for 3 to 5 minutes. During this time, a gray, foamy "scum" will rise to the surface; this is the proteinaceous material that causes cloudiness.33
Drain the pot entirely and discard the blanching water.
Rinse the chicken and wings under cold running water. Use a brush or fingers to remove any remaining coagulated bits from the chicken cavity and joints.5
Thoroughly wash the pressure cooker pot to ensure no protein residue remains on the interior walls.4
b) Botanical Preparation and Purification
The vegetables must be prepared to maximize surface area while ensuring no grit is introduced, particularly from the leek tops.
Leek Top De-Gritting: Slice the dark green leek tops lengthwise into quarters. Submerge them in a large bowl of cold water and agitate vigorously. Sand and soil, which are often trapped in the inner layers, will sink to the bottom. Lift the leeks out and repeat the process with fresh water until no sediment remains.28
Celeriac Paring: Use a chef’s knife to cut the thick, knobby skin away from the celeriac. Peeling is insufficient for this root; the outer 1/4 inch must be removed to reach the clean, white flesh. Cut the celeriac into 1-inch cubes.24
Parsnip and Onion: Peel the parsnips and slice into 1-inch rounds. Peel the white onion and cut into quarters. To keep the cloves from getting lost, pin them directly into one of the onion quarters (the oignon piqué technique).2
Mushroom Prep: Wipe the mushroom stems clean of any substrate or peat moss. Leave them whole or halved.30
c) Pressurized Extraction Sequence
The core of the process involves the careful management of the 12 PSI thermal curve.
Combine the blanched poultry, prepared mirepoix blanc, mushroom stems, white peppercorns, and bouquet garni in the pressure cooker pot.
Add cold filtered water until the ingredients are just covered. Do not exceed the "Max Fill" line of the vessel, as this can cause the pressure valve to clog with protein foam.7
Secure and lock the lid. Set the pressure setting to high (12 PSI).
Apply medium-high heat until the vessel reaches full pressure. As soon as the regulator indicates 12 PSI has been achieved, reduce the heat to the lowest possible setting that maintains the pressure.4
Set the timer for 120 minutes (2 hours). This duration is optimized for a whole bird at 12 PSI to ensure the marrow is fully extracted.4
Critical Step: At the end of the 120-minute cycle, turn off the heat and allow the pressure to release naturally. This process (NPR) takes approximately 30 to 45 minutes. Never use the quick-release valve; the sudden drop in pressure will cause the stock to boil violently, emulsifying the fat and destroying the clarity.7
d) Refining and Lipid Management
The stock must be filtered and de-fatted to ensure it does not overwhelm the delicate leek flavor with heavy grease.
Carefully open the lid once the pressure indicator has fully dropped.
Using a slotted spoon, gently lift out the large solids and discard them. Do not squeeze the vegetables or chicken, as this will release fine particulates into the liquid.33
Strain the liquid through a fine-mesh sieve lined with cheesecloth or a nut milk bag into a large bowl. For the highest degree of clarity, do not pour the last half-cup of liquid if it contains heavy sediment.4
Rapidly cool the stock in an ice bath to preserve its fresh flavor.11
Refrigerate the stock overnight. The chicken fat (schmaltz) will rise to the top and solidify into a hard, white disk.
Lift the fat disk off and discard it (or save for sautéing the leeks for the soup). The resulting liquid should be a pale, translucent jelly—this is the sign of a master-level extraction.1
The Biochemical Impact on Potato-Leek Gastronomy
The resulting stock is a highly concentrated solution of Type II collagen and aromatic volatiles. In a potato-leek soup (such as Vichyssoise or Potage Parmentier), the interaction between the stock and the starch is the defining technical characteristic.
Starch Stabilization and Gelatin Viscosity
When potatoes are simmered in this stock, the gelatin acts as a hydrocolloid. As the starch granules hydrate and swell, the gelatin provides a protective matrix that prevents the granules from bursting and releasing too much amylopectin into the liquid.14 This is especially important if the soup is to be blended. A water-based potato soup often becomes "gummy" when processed in a high-speed blender; however, a gelatin-rich stock provides the structural integrity necessary to maintain a silky, cream-like texture without the need for excessive dairy.7
The Flavor Profile of Mirepoix Blanc at 115°C
Cooking mirepoix blanc under pressure at  creates a different flavor profile than atmospheric simmering. Under pressure, the sulfur compounds in the leek tops and onions are forced back into the liquid rather than escaping as steam.8 This results in a stock that has a more profound "allium" punch, which perfectly mirrors the primary flavor of the leeks in the soup. The celeriac and parsnip provide a base of sweetness and earthiness that rounds out the sharp notes of the alliums, creating a "long" finish on the palate.2
The inclusion of mushroom stems is a modernist technique to increase the density of natural glutamates. Because leeks and potatoes are relatively low in protein, the mushroom-enriched chicken stock provides the necessary "umami weight" to make the soup feel satisfying as a main course.6 By using white stems, the chef ensures that this depth is achieved without darkening the soup's final color.
Conclusions on Mastery and Execution
A master stock is not merely an ingredient but the structural foundation of the final dish. By utilizing the 12 PSI pressure environment, the chef can achieve a level of gelatin extraction in two hours that would otherwise take a full day of traditional simmering. The specific substitution of celeriac and parsnip, combined with the rigorous blanching of the whole chicken and wings, ensures a product that is both aesthetically pure and physically robust. This stock provides the essential viscosity, umami, and aromatic complexity required to elevate a standard potato-leek soup into a world-class gastronomic experience. The focus on lipid management and sediment filtration ensures that the final soup remains elegant, clear, and focused on the bright, sweet interplay of the leek and the potato.


===================================================
SOUP PREPARATION 
===================================================

1) prepare for ingredients
    a) thinly slice the leeks (750g)
    b) dice the yellow onion (100g)
    c) thinly slice the shallots (1/2 cup)
    d) mince the 3 cloves garlic (~1 tbsp)
    e) create a cartouche
    f) cube the potatoes, 1/2 inch, ~3.3 lbs (after peeling)
    g) create a bouquet garni of the bay leaves / thyme / parsley 

2) render the bacon fat 
    a) fry 5 strips of bacon in a triple-ply stainless steel soup pot  
    b) keep 2 tbsp of the bacon fat, discard the rest
    c) put the bacon in the fridge for garnish later

3) sweat the aromatics
    a) turn the heat on medium-low, the pot should be ~285F
    b) add to the pot:
        - 3 tbsp butter 
        - 1.5 tbsp olive oil (layering these fats ensures it doesn't taste all like bacon or butter)
    c) once the butter begins to foam, add the following: 
        - leeks 
        - onions 
        - shallots 
    d) stir to coat the vegetables in the fat 
    e) add 1/2 tsp salt (this facilitates osmosis)
    f) add the cartouche 
    g) sweat the vegetables for 15 minutes 
    h) add the minced garlic
    g) cook an additional 2 minutes, until the garlic is translucent. 
        If the garlic starts to develop color, add stock to lower the surface temperature.


4) add the potatoes 
    a) add the cubed yukon gold potatoes to the pot 
        stir them in and mix everything
    b) cook for 3-5 minutes. 
        coating the potatoes with fat helps protect their surface, preventing them from disintegrating in the broth later.

5) simmer
    a) pour 2.5 quarts of chicken stock into the pot
    b) bring the mixture to a boil
    c) reduce heat to low
    d) simmer between 185-205F (the potatoes will cook without being tossed too aggressively, keeping them intact)
    e) simmer partially covered for 30-40 minutes
        the potatoes must be soft enough that they crumble when pressed against the side of the pot with a spoon
    f) halfway through add 1 tsp salt

6) rice the potatoes 
    a) remove the bouquet garni 
    b) trasnfer the potatoes to a large bowl (soup them out) 
    c) blend the rest of the soup with an immersion blender until smooth 
    d) strain the soup through a fine-mesh seive to remove any remaining fibrous allium strands
    d) press the cooked potatoes through a potato ricer directly into the strained broth. 
        use the finest setting on the ricer (ensure every bit of potato is aerated with minimal shear). 
    e) use a hand whisk to mix riced potatoes with the broth. 

7) add the dairy
    a) in a small saucepan, warm 1/2 cup of heavy cream to 140F 
    b) cube 2 tbsp of butter
    c) take the soup pot off the heat, and wait until it's ~160F 
    d) whisk in the cubed butter 1 at a time
        160F is hot enough to melt the butter but low enough to maintain a stable emulsion
    e) whisk in the warmed cream
    f) whisk in the 1/2 cup buttermilk 
    g) add the 1.5 tbsp white miso

8) season to finish
    g) add the white pepper, 1 tsp
    h) add the nutmeg, 1/4 tsp
    i) add 1-2 tsp of salt to taste 
    j) stir in 1 tbsp fresh lemon juice 

===================================================
SERVING
===================================================

The ideal serving temperature is 160F.
    At this temperature, the aromatic compounds of hte leek are most active, and the butter is at its most palatable. 

If in season, a few shavings of black truffle or a drizzle of truffle oil (not synthetic) can elevate the flavors. 

You can also serve it with the bacon that was cooked earlier. 

THe soups the starches will continue to retrograde as the soup cools. 
    This often results in the soup becoming significantly thicker in the refrigerator
    When reheating, because the starch has tightened, the soup will require a splash of stock or milk to return to its consistency.

To prevent bacterial growth and maintain color, the soup should be cooled in an ice bath if possible.
Potato-based soups generally do not freeze well.
    The cell walls collapse and the emulsion separates during the freeze-thaw cycle, resulting in a grainy texture.


